<TEXT>
the justice department says it has no objection 
to the changes to the city charter that were approved by voters 
last month 
news of the approval came in a letter to frederick ao schwarz 
jr chairman of the charter revision commission from acting 
assistant attorney general james p turner of the departments 
civil rights division 
our work is now done schwarz said the foundation has 
been laid for a more representative fairer and efficient city 
government 
schwarz a former city corporation counsel noted that turners 
letter calls particular attention to the fact that minority 
voters will likely have an increased opportunity to elect members 
of the enlarged and more powerful city council 
increasing minority representation in the city government was 
one of the charter revision commissions major goals he said 
although turner wrote that the department interposes no 
objection to the revised charter he added that federal law 
allows the option of going to court in the future to enjoin the 
enforcement of these changes 
the revised charter abolishes the board of estimate and 
transfers its fiscal and planning powers to the mayor the city 
council and other city officials it also increases the size of the 
council from 35 to 51 members 
the board of estimate had been declared unconstitutional because 
it gave equal representation to each borough despite wide 
disparities in population 
city council majority leader peter vallone who has long pushed 
for abolition of the board of estimate and a more equitable balance 
of power between the citys executive and legislative branches 
also praised the departments decision 
</TEXT>
