legislation and national security on tuesday 
the arrangements which pool health care coverage for small 
employers who cant get coverage from larger insurance carriers 
were created under the federal employee retirement income security 
act 
states generally regulate insurance and require cash reserves to 
back claims witnesses told the government operations committees 
subcommittee the health insurance arrangements generally do not 
maintain reserves to pay claims said raymond maria acting 
inspector general for the labor department 
ms petersen acknowledged that the reserve requirements would 
hurt many beneficial operators 
with the expectation of staying afloat for a period of time 
through aggressive selling and slow claims payment these 
fraudulent arrangements have become a variation of the classic 
ponzi scheme maria said many operators abscond with the funds 
leaving the workers high and dry the two witnesses said 
some 5 million such arrangements exist nationwide maria said 
the number of fraudulent ones is unknown 
