<TEXT>
lucky for thakorial mistry there are no 
sacred cows in his business 
mistry is probably the only hindu taxidermist in the world it 
might seem strange that a hindu would make a living stuffing and 
mounting animals for hindus revere living creatures and believe in 
reincarnation 
the people in his hometown outside bombay india were mostly 
vegetarians and would never kill an animal he said only the 
poorest and hungriest would eat a chicken but only behind closed 
doors 
no wonder that mistry was considered an oddball or worse 
when he began his boyhood hobby of taxidermy his first specimen 
was a pigeon which he grabbed in the rafters of his home 
chloroformed and stuffed with cotton 
it didnt turn out real good but it looked good to me until 
it started to smell mistry said 
the boy bagged small birds and chipmunks with a bb gun and 
stuffed them in the privacy of his attic bedroom mistrys secret 
escaped the notice of his father the town blacksmith and a devout 
hindu but his neighborhood pals were fascinated 
i always enjoyed opening animals he said i love animals 
my friends thought i was crazy but when i finished they thought i 
had created something beautiful even my parents when they found 
out they liked it too 
mistry arrived in the united states in 1971 with a degree in 
chemistry and zoology about 6 in his pocket and plans for a 
career in medical technology however he said my hobby turned 
into a living after an apprenticeship with taxidermy shops in 
maryland and virginia he went into business for himself in 1976 
his large studio in this rural community south of washington 
dc is filled with striking examples of mistrys artistry 
including deer bear bison pheasant peacocks fish and big game 
from alaska to africa 
beneath a mounted shark a red fox leaps after a pair of grouse 
rising in flight two gamecocks lunge in battle their neck 
feathers bristling 
mistry 43 assisted by his wife jyotsna stuffs about 1000 
creatures annually at prices ranging from 6 an inch for 
freshwater fish to as much as 2000 for a grizzly bear 
business is profitable enough for mistry who became a us 
citizen in 1979 to support his family of four and to help nearly 
two dozen relatives immigrate from india 
lounging on the marble floor of his showroom is one customers 
unclaimed white pekinese dog one of many small pets that mistry 
has lovingly freezedried for their grieving owners 
the pekinese would make a dandy doorstop but mistry says its 
so lifelike that it makes a good guard dog to scare wouldbe 
intruders peering through the windows 
mistry recalls with a grin the time a husband called to ask 
can you stuff my wife on another occasion a lawyer telephoned 
to say his client had written a will requesting that his body be 
freezedried 
mistry turned them both down i could do a human being but 
its illegal he said even if it were legal i wouldnt do 
it 
how does he feel about stuffing a cow the most sacred animal in 
the hindu religion 
sure i could do a cow mistry replied no problem youve 
got to change to survive wherever you go this is america 
