<TEXT>
president bush is extending steel import 
restraints on 28 trading partners while giving the nations 
incentives to stop subsidizing their steel industries 
renewal of the curbs through march 1992 will eliminate 
tradedistorting practices in the steel sector bush said in a 
statement tuesday 
the old pacts negotiated by the reagan administration in 1984 
expired on sept 30 
the legislation signed by bush authorizes the federal government 
to continue the curbs for another 2 years the curbs negotiated 
individually with leading steelexporting nations place annual 
productbyproduct limits on the volume of steel that can be 
shipped to the united states 
negotiators in the office of us trade representative carla 
hills announced tuesday that the talks had been recently completed 
with all nations targeted by the administration the talks had to 
be conducted before bush signed the bill so that the import program 
would not lapse 
the resulting new pacts will hold the foreign share of the us 
steel market to 191 percent in the first year of the program 
hills said in a statement 
she said import restraint agreements had been finalized with the 
12nation european community and australia austria brazil 
czechoslovakia east germany finland hungary japan south korea 
mexico the peoples republic of china poland romania trinidad 
and tobago venezuela and yugoslavia 
bushs signature on the steel trade liberalization act had 
been expected for some time 
not only did bush promise to renew import curbs during the 1988 
campaign but his administration orchestrated a compromise last 
summer between lawmakers favoring a fiveyear extension of the 
restraints and congressional opponents who wanted the program ended 
the idea behind the original pacts was to give domestic 
steelmakers breathing space from subsidized foreign competition 
many steelstate lawmakers had pushed the administration to 
extend the curbs for another five years but bush opted for a 
smallerscale program in deference to steelusing manufacturers 
the manufacturers argued that the quotas have driven up prices and 
caused supply shortages of some steel products 
bush called the countrybycounty agreements a stepping 
stone to the day when all tradedistorting subsidies could be 
eliminated 
the program is structured to give nations incentives to trade 
freely 
for example the pacts allow some countries market shares to 
rise by 1 percentage point per year until quotas are phased out 
entirely at the end of the program hills said the yearly increase 
will be allocated to nations that exhibit the most willingness to 
stop subsidizing their domestic steelmakers 
some nations have already been granted such status hills said 
she identified those tuesday as the european community japan 
south korea brazil mexico australia and trinidad and tobago 
</TEXT>
