<TEXT>
the interior department is allowing many 
violations of environmental regulations under its oil and gas 
leasing program because of lax monitoring according to an internal 
audit 
the report by the departments inspector generals office said 
tuesday that oil and gas lease operators on federal or indian lands 
who commit violations often do so without fear of being 
punished because civil penalties are rarely assessed 
even when lease operators are shown to be repeat offenders 
their poor record often was swept clean without monetary penalties 
if corrections on specific violations were made the investigators 
added 
the report covered the federal bureau of land managements 
scrutiny of oil and gas leases throughout the west during a 
twoyear period beginning in fiscal 1988 
investigators focused on activities in eight bureau offices with 
jurisdiction over more than 39000 oil and gas wells about half of 
those under the federal program all the wells are either on 
federal or indian land 
bureau spokesman bob johns said the agency was reviewing the 
report but that the bureau agreed generally with many of the 
findings and recommendations a formal response by the agency is 
expected to be completed by february he said 
violations of existing regulations have resulted in 
environmental damage lost or unpaid royalties and a potentially 
substantial government liability for plugging abandoned wells and 
cleaning up well sites the report said 
the report said that during fiscal 1988 federal inspectors 
uncovered 1317 violations of environmental regulations and other 
infractions but assessed only 11500 in penalties 
among the violations were 277 that were considered major 
the report said 
in many cases however environmental violations and 
questionable activities by lease holders went unnoticed because of 
inadequate checks on well abandonments venting practices and other 
activities the investigators said 
among the findings were 
lease operators are being widely allowed to abandon wells 
without getting required government approval leaving no clear 
picture as to how many wells are productive or whether abandoned 
wells have been properly closed 
in some cases wells were found to have been abandoned 15 years 
or more without an authorized inspectors approval and certainty of 
their environmental condition 
unauthorized venting or flaring of natural gas some dating to 
the 1960s is widespread among lease operators posing 
environmental concerns and preventing the government from 
collecting royalties about 291000 for an estimated 1 billion 
cubic feet of gas in the limited number of cases documented 
bonding requirements are inadequate to protect against smaller 
lease operators abandoning sites without taking proper 
environmental precautions in many cases the government will have 
to assume responsibility 
there could be a significant number of wells throughout the 
country which are either plugged improperly or not plugged and 
these wells could be adversely impacting the environment the 
report said 
the cost of potentially capping some 22000 wells in question 
was put at more than 300 million 
some of the cases cited involved 
a montana lease holder who was told he had to test only nine of 
his 150 wells to determine whether all of them should be considered 
temporarily closed operating or be in line for capping they did 
not want to overburden him the report said 
a california lease purchaser who was allowed to buy 30 closed 
or temporarily abandoned wells with a bond of only 25000 after 
he filed for bankruptcy without capping any of the wells the 
government was left with a 378000 bill 
a lease operator who was shown on videotape dumping extracted 
saltwater into an unlined unauthorized pit in violation of 
environmental regulations although the operator was told in 35 
letters over a twomonth period to correct the practice no 
monetary penalty was assessed 
a well on indian land that blew after a lease holder began 
extracting natural gas without having conducted promised pressure 
tests he was fined only 5000 although up to 4 million cubic feet 
of gas a day were released over 65 days causing the evacuation of 
nearby residents and raising concern that local water supplies may 
have been contaminated 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

