intention to maintain segregated schools 
but seymour wrote rogers erred by limiting the school 
districts burden merely to showing that it had nondiscriminatory 
reasons for acting as it did as 30 years of desegregation law have 
made clear the constitution requires more than ceasing to promote 
segregation 
baldock argued the schools had done enough the school board 
has demonstrated concern for improving the racial composition in 
the topeka schools while retaining the neighborhood school concept 
in some places the two are not compatible but in this system 
substantial integration has been achieved 
rich jones an attorney for the parents who sought the cases 
reopening said lawyers will key on the dissenting opinion 
this is the first time we get to see the dissent he said 
the school district will be in a position to make a decision 
the attorney for the school district joe zima said the board 
plans to schedule a meeting early next week to consider it actions 
zima said the school district could ask all 10 judges on the 
court of appeals to hear the case ask the us supreme court to 
hear the case or go before rogers to help fashion a solution 
</TEXT>
