<TEXT>
more than a dozen reports of problems with rudder 
controls on boeing 737s have been made since a plane skidded off a 
new york airport runway with such a problem two federal agencies 
say 
the federal aviation administration and the national 
transportation safety board said tuesday they have asked the boeing 
co to provide data on any reports it has received before or since 
the new york accident on rudders set in unexpected positions on its 
737300 and 737400 model jets 
the faa will use the information to decide whether to order any 
action such as a design change or modification said faa spokesman 
david duff in seattle 
ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz in washington dc said the 
agency had received at least a dozen reports two involving foreign 
airlines of instances where the crew says it discovered the 
rudder was trimmed in a way that they didnt expect 
the faa has looked into the incidents to try to determine if 
the cause was related to human factors or a mechanical problem or a 
combination of both duff said 
the inquiries are limited to the boeing 737300 and 737400 
models because they have electrically driven controls earlier 
737100 and 737200 models have manual cranks 
ntsb investigators found that the rudder was improperly set on a 
usair jet trying to take off from laguardia airport on sept 20 
the 737400 veered on the runway and the crew aborted takeoff but 
the plane skidded into the east river the plane broke into three 
pieces and two passengers were killed and 45 injured 
the investigations will look into whether a crew member 
inadvertently activated the rudder switch and examine the cockpit 
gauge that indicates how the rudder is set duff said 
boeing commercial planes spokesman dick schleh said the firm is 
compiling the data for investigators 
