<TEXT>
sixty percent of american workers favor 
onthejob drug testing according to a gallup poll released 
wednesday by a corporate group that said the results give a green 
light to increased employer testing 
the survey done for a newly formed organization of 14 large 
corporations concerned about employers rights said workers tended 
to support some programs over others 
for example 51 percent of the 1007 employees polled indicated 
that companies should have the right to randomly test any employee 
for drug use support rose to 70 percent for testing employees 
suspected of drug usage 
twentyfour percent of the workers said they had seen or heard 
of drug use by coworkers on the job 
on the broadest question 60 percent of the sample said they 
favored their company adopting some sort of drugtesting policy 
not counted were 9 percent whose employers already have such a 
program support for testing was strongest from workers in rural 
areas those 55 and older and those with an education of high 
school or less 
fourteen percent of those who did not attend college opposed 
drug testing at their company compared to 28 percent for those 
with a college degree and 48 percent for those who had done 
postgraduate work 
workers attitudes are far more conservative than we had 
anticipated mark a de bernardo executive director of the new 
institute for a drugfree workplace said in a statement 
employees simply do not want to tolerate working with drug 
abusers on the job de bernardo said more significantly the 
survey reaffirms the policy of increasing numbers of employers who 
are drug testing and gives a clear and unmistakable green light to 
further testing of employees and job applicants 
the national labor relations board said in june that employers 
cannot unilaterally begin testing unionized workers for drug use 
but can test job applicants regardless of whether unions object 
the board said employee testing falls under collective bargaining 
and therefore must be the subject of unionmanagement negotiations 
there was no immediate comment from the aflcio to the survey 
which did show employee reservations about drug testing 
in one question only 26 percent of respondents agreed that 
testing was a necessity fortytwo percent said it should be 
done despite reservations while 29 percent said it invaded privacy 
and should be done only under limited circumstances 
the workers gave their highest support for drug testing of 
workers in safetysensitive jobs 
the 14 corporatons in the institute each have some sort of 
drugtesting program de bernardo said 
they are bellsouth corp of atlanta capital citiesabc inc 
philadelphia dow chemical usa midland mich georgiapacific 
corp atlanta goodyear tire amp rubber co akron ohio hoffmanla 
roche inc nutley nj ibm corp white plains ny johnson amp 
johnson new brunswick nj mobil oil new york motorola inc 
schaumberg ill pfizer inc new york texaco inc white plains 
ny texas instruments dallas and 3m co st paul minn 
the institute hired the gallup organization which interviewed a 
random sample of 1007 fulltime workers around the nation last 
month fortytwo percent of those surveyed described their 
occupation as professional 25 percent as blue collar 20 percent 
as managerial and 10 percent as secretarial or clerical the rest 
were other or refused to answer the question 
the survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 31 percent 
