<TEXT>
sirens wailed across poland at noon 
wednesday to mark the eighth anniversary of the 1981 martiallaw 
crackdown which lech walesa declared should be a reminder of the 
need for pluralism and tolerance 
hundreds of young people took to the streets in five cities 
however hurling rocks and firebombs to express anger at the 
crackdown and demand punishment for those responsible 
in the most open discussion to date of the decision newspapers 
were filled with articles examining gen wojciech jaruzelskis dec 
13 1981 declaration to suppress the solidarity labor movement 
before december 1981 solidarity did not appreciate the 
strength of the authorities jaruzelski told solidaritys gazeta 
wyborcza newspaper after december 1981 the authorities did not 
appreciate the strength of solidarity 
in the crackdown carried out with military precision 
communication to the outside world was cut thousands of solidarity 
activists were rounded up and interned the union was ordered 
suspended and at least nine miners died resisting authorities 
eight years after the event solidarity has not only regained 
legal status but it has taken control of the government from the 
communist party however activists allowed jaruzelski to be 
elected president in july with the minimum number of votes required 
while older solidarity activists approached the anniversary 
somberly hundreds of demonstrators in katowice hurled firebombs 
and paint at the doors of the provincial party headquarters state 
radio reported 
in szczecin several hundred teenagers rallied and marched to 
police headquarters where they burned jaruzelski in effigy chanted 
down with communism and threw stones and bottles at the 
building before police turned water cannons on them radio said 
a group of demonstrators attacked police headquarters with 
stones in wroclaw and officers responded with truncheons the state 
pap news agency reported smaller anticommunist marches also took 
place outside the national communist party headquarters in warsaw 
and according to state television in krakow 
in his message to mark the anniversary walesa muted his 
criticism while stressing that there should be efforts at 
reconciliation 
whether polish national interests required the implementation of 
martial law is a question that belongs to historians walesa 
said 
however one does not need scientific analysis to see the 
senselessness of the human losses and persecutions the campaign of 
slanders and humiliations the cult of force and the pacifying of 
public life 
today the tragedy of martial law reminds us of the need for 
cultured politics pluralism and tolerance the dramatic 
experiences of those days cannot be repeated because among other 
things we are wiser from those experiences 
the tragedy of martial law cannot overshadow the future and 
the squaring of accounts cannot replace the striving for a just and 
prosperous poland walesa said 
government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska said the date 
has deep meaning for her especially sitting in a government where 
literally those who eight years ago were arrested and those who 
gave and signed the orders sit side by side 
the fact the two sides could overcome their differences proves 
that those eight years which were very hard and brought a lot of 
misfortunes were not wasted they became a lesson for both sides 
the communist side became convinced that without the participation 
of society it is not possible to govern the opposition was shown 
that relentlessness in striving for freedom has got to be combined 
with political realism 
government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska said the date 
has deep meaning for her especially sitting in a government where 
literally those who eight years ago were arrested and those who 
gave and signed the orders sit side by side 
the fact the two sides could overcome their differences proves 
that those eight years which were very hard and brought a lot of 
misfortunes were not wasted they became a lesson for both sides 
the communist side became convinced that without the participation 
of society it is not possible to govern the opposition was shown 
that relentlessness in striving for freedom has got to be combined 
with political realism 
solidarity had called on factories nationwide to sound sirens at 
noon in memory of the day still vividly and painfully remembered 
among those interviewed by the communist party weekly polityka 
were col wieslaw gornicki jaruzelskis close aide who said at 
the time he believed martial law was inevitable although today he 
is unsure whether moderates on both sides could have prevented it 
gornicki said the public should remember soviet pressure on 
poland and soviet leader leonid i brezhnevs threats about 
which the public still knows too little 
at a march 1982 meeting with jaruzelski brezhnev sneered 
that martial law was a lamentable half measure and authorities 
should be even tougher gornicki said 
interior minister czeslaw kiszczak whose police and riot troops 
carried out the crackdown told the newspaper he regrets the 
injustice and harm that people feel but that as a historical 
experience martial law turned out to be educative and valuable 
from this experience stems the success of dialogue and todays 
essentially changing poland he said 
in a commentary gazeta wyborcza said it is possible to discuss 
martial law in a calmer way 
justified nonviolent resistance to martial law and loyalty to 
solidarity through the difficult years finally allowed a historic 
breakthrough it said though the price we have had to pay is 
great all those years were not a lost time 
