<TEXT>
two dozen western nations that are 
coordinating a massive aid package for hungary and poland on 
wednesday offered similar help to other east european nations 
moving toward democracy and market economies 
the foreign ministers of the 24 nations ending a oneday 
meeting said they would respond positively to those nations 
shedding communism 
the 24 would welcome requests for aid from other states 
the ministers said they mentioned east germany czechoslovakia 
bulgaria and yugoslavia 
the donor countries including the 12 european community 
nations the united states japan australia and canada 
stressed the importance of the economic and political reform 
process in the soviet union 
but they did not overtly offer aid to moscow sources said 
moscow may need more aid than any other east european nation but 
it would have been diplomatically unwise to put it on the list of 
wouldbe recipient nations 
us secretary of state james a baker iii told the meeting we 
cannot ignore democratic reforms elsewhere in eastern europe 
these showed our efforts at coordinating western responses are 
addressing only the first phase of the challenge of economic and 
political reform in eastern europe he said 
western aid for poland and hungary is being coordinated by the 
ec at the request of the leaders of the seven most industrialized 
nations who met in paris in july well before the reform movements 
in other east european nations began to take root 
to date officials said aid totaling up to 6 billion over 
several years has been granted or committed to poland and hungary 
it ranges from emergency food to longterm export and investment 
credits 
on wednesday the united states west germany japan and nine 
other countries formally underwrote a stabilization fund of 1 
billion to prop up the zloty the polish currency and help make it 
convertible 
west germany will pay 250 million to the fund the united 
states 200 million and japan 150 million 
britain france and italy will each contribute 100 million and 
the remainder will come from canada spain portugal switzerland 
austria and turkey 
baker called the fund critical for the success of the currency 
and price reforms in poland 
the fund is also taking on symbolic importance for the poles 
an indicator of whether the west will in fact stand with them when 
they make hard economic decisions he added 
he said in addition to paying into the stabilization fund the 
united states is granting poland another 800 million in a range of 
programs including investment credits food and medical aid and 
trade guarantees 
poland has a foreign debt of 40 billion hungarys is half 
that yet it is the highest per capita in eastern europe 
the 24 donor nations also discussed a 1 billion loan to help 
improve the hungarian economy some are considering creating a 
development bank for eastern europe 
the hungarian loan will be made once budapest accepts 
international monetary fund conditions to overhaul its economy 
which would also free funds from the world bank and other western 
sources 
both hungary and poland are near an agreement with the imf 
imf managing director michel camdessus said monday a letter of 
intent for a 700 million loan agreement with poland could be 
initialed this week 
the united states will put 200 million toward a 500 million 
temporary loan for poland as it awaits help from the imf the white 
house said 
polish foreign minister krzysztof skubiszewski and gyula horn 
his hungarian counterpart outlined to the western donors their 
economic reforms 
one of our most important aims is to shape a healthy 
enterprise structure horn said our top priority is to 
maintain the countrys creditworthiness and to assure access to 
normal market financial resources that enable us to fulfill our 
farreaching political and economic objectives 
skubiszewski outlined his countrys efforts to demonopolize 
the polish economy by opening wider the doors to free 
enterprise 
