<TEXT>
white house chief of staff john h sununu 
confessed to the national press club on wednesday that the bush 
administration has made a lot of mistakes some of them unreported 
doozies 
thus ended his confession 
sununu not only refused to shed light on the flubs but devoted 
most of an hour to a glowing review of the administration five 
weeks shy of its first birthday that left practically no 
superlative unsaid 
he called george bush probably the most underrated man in 
modern history to serve in the presidency 
sununu who said his aim was to influence the journalists 
yearend analyses said bush is getting raves too in polls that 
show his approval ratings in the midtohigh 70s numbers that 
truly are virtually unprecedented in history 
from the savings and loan bailout to the war on drugs bush has 
set the agenda and shown an ability to work with the 
democratcontrolled congress without sacrificing his principles 
the former new hampshire governor argued 
bush has really excelled in shaping and encouraging the 
dramatic changes toward democracy in the soviet bloc sununu said 
it was not an easy year george bush just made it seem easy 
said sununu 
he said bush has resisted the temptation to make instant 
foreign policy or snap conclusions 
the one thing the president understands is that you dont get 
extra credit for running out and doing it immediately on 
television he said 
he has handled the east bloc changes as one would handle 
landing a 10pound fish on 2pound line avoiding the temptation 
to jerk that line and to try to pull the fish in all at once 
sununu also hailed his boss as the master of the small 
gesture from inviting french president francois mitterrand to 
his kennebunkport maine seaside home to taking egyptian president 
hosni mubarak out to a baseball game to his countless hours on 
the telephone with foreign leaders 
sununu even suggested that the lunch bush held on his july visit 
to poland for both communist leaders and solidarity members laid 
the groundwork for the new solidarityled government in poland 
that in turn he said served as the catalyst for the very rapid 
change taking place in eastern europe 
under questioning sununu defended bushs controversial decision 
to send two top aides to china last saturday to rekindle ties with 
that communist government six months after a brutal crackdown on 
prodemocracy demonstrators 
bush recognizes that theres a billion people there and he 
wanted to recreate a relationship that would allow whatever 
pressures we put on to be taken as credible said sununu 
asked about the possibility of us aid for east germany sununu 
said west germany will be the first to help and the nato allies 
will await evidence of internal changes before putting together any 
aid package like the one crafted for poland 
the administration has seldom seen internal quarrels spill out 
into the press and sununu was asked how the white house managed 
that a rare achievement in recent administrations 
it has a calm lowkeyed mildmannered chief of staff who 
doesnt get upset at anything said the imperious sununu evoking 
laughter loudest from his own aides 
any regrets weve made a lot of mistakes a couple of them 
youve caught most of them you havent there have been some 
doozies that you missed 
mmmmm how about an example his lips are sealed and he added 
im not even going to write a book 
