<TEXT>
jennifer casolos friends and parents 
expressed gratitude and relief wednesday at the news that the 
church worker was being released from the salvadoran prison where 
shed been held on terrorism charges 
i am deeply greatly grateful to each and every one who has 
believed in jennifer and her innocence her mother audrey 
casolo told a news conference in us sen christopher dodds 
whethersfield office just south of hartford 
casolo 28 was arrested nov 26 after a raid on her house in 
san salvador and was accused of storing weapons for leftist 
rebels police said they found thousands of rounds of sovietmade 
ammunition and other armaments in the garden behind her home 
salvadoran president alfredo christiani announced wednesday that 
casolo 28 had been released because of insufficient evidence and 
would be deported shortly afterwards reporters saw the thomaston 
native leave ilopango prison with us ambassador william walker 
you dont know whether to laugh because youre happy or cry 
because youre happy said susanna wallace of the christian 
education seminar in san antonio the lay church group that sent 
casolo to the central american country in 1985 
we hope this helps stop the persecution of church workers 
thats going on in el salvador wallace said weeping as she 
spoke this confirms our standing all along of her innocence 
in whethersfield casolos father john thanked volunteers and 
officials for bringing our daughter home 
in thomaston a western connecticut town of 7000 people the 
initial shock and disbelief over casolos arrest 2 weeks ago was 
replaced by an effort to win her freedom 
a hastily arranged prayer vigil drew 250 people and raised 
1000 teachers started a legal defense fund and other organized a 
letter and christmas cardwriting drive 
word of casolos release spread quickly at thomaston high 
school where casolo was student body president 10 years ago 
all the faculty here are extremely elated that shell be 
coming back home to us said teacher walter robinson word got 
around very very quickly from room to room to room 
a decade ago casolo was a cheerful popular high school senior 
more interested in cheering on the basketball team than changing 
the world 
casolo who came from a working classfamily finished at the 
top of her class and honors came easily to her in addition to 
being chosen student body president she was the yearbook editor 
and was voted most ambitious most creative and did the most for 
thomaston high school 
she was the hit of the school edward wilkinson now a vice 
principal at the school said tuesday she was very intelligent 
inquisitive a bundle of energy if anything needed to be started 
for school spirit or something she would always do it 
friends described her as a compassionate caring teenager but 
said there was little sign of the spirituality casolo would find 
working among el salvadors poor 
her parents divorced while she was a student her mother 
supported the family by working as a bookkeeper at a vocational 
high school in waterbury 
friends say casolo became more religious and more interested in 
social work while at brandeis university a prestigious liberal 
arts college in waltham mass 
she took a double major in american studies and latin american 
studies was captain of the soccer team and graduated summa cum 
laude 
friends say casolo experienced anxiety about choosing a career 
torn between an attraction to social work and a feeling of 
obligation to find a wellpaying job to help her mother 
social work won out after working with salvadoran refugees in 
seattle casolo who is fluent in spanish left for el salvador 
she worked for christian education seminars which organizes visits 
for prominent americans to el salvador 
i think that she was something she felt called to do rather 
than simply take a job and make a lot of money said susan 
abbott a close friend from high school 
the work put her in close contact with a wide range of 
salvadorans from president christiani and military leaders to 
church leaders and opposition party politicians 
casolo quickly formed a spiritual attachment to the country and 
its people particularly the poor 
in a letter to a friend she spoke of joining the catholic 
church to become a nun in another letter she wrote im a 
pastor without religion only with lots of love 
even after her arrest casolo remained upbeat shouting her 
claims of innocence to us reporters at her arraignment and 
describing her imprisonment as a lifechanging experience 
i cant say i have faith in the system to find me innocent 
she said but i believe my innocence will shine through 
</TEXT>
