<TEXT>
on july 18 1863 despite fatigue and poor rations the 54th 
massachusetts colored volunteer infantry marched across a halfmile 
of sand on a south carolina beach to lead the illplanned attack on 
fort wagner in charleston harbor the regiment lost more than 40 
percent of its men 
the story of the 54th the first black regiment from the north 
to fight in the civil war and its youthful white colonel robert 
gould shaw unfolds in glory edward zwicks masterful movie 
for tristar pictures 
zwick presents a powerful moving tapestry of wars 
senselessness the screenplay by kevin jarre is partly based on the 
books lay this laurel and one gallant rush and letters 
shaw wrote home to his parents the movie narrated by matthew 
broderick as shaw is largely seen through his eyes 
young and privileged but disillusioned and battlescarred after 
the gory and indecisive battle of antietam shaw returns to his 
wealthy powerful and abolitionist parents in massachusetts just in 
time for a lavish party and an offer from the governor to take 
command of an allblack fighting regiment 
he rises in rank from captain to colonel and musters his men 
who include his childhood friends cabot cary elwes who is white 
and becomes a major and tom andre braugher a secondgeneration 
free black who volunteers as an enlisted man 
much of glory focuses on the basic training of a ragtag 
group of runaway slaves and free men who are denied all the basic 
supplies given to white soldiers including proper shoes and the 
coveted blue uniform and are asked to accept less pay 
they have much to learn about soldiering and about human 
relations in a fight for freedom and the restoration of the union 
as trip an embittered runaway denzel washington cry 
freedom the mighty quinn power does a star turn his 
hatred desires feelings are worn on his face such as when hes 
flogged for supposedly trying to desert not one word is uttered 
he merely locks eyes with broderick biloxi blues war 
games and allows a single tear to fall broderick meanwhile 
shows clear repulsion and sorrow why because the whip a symbol 
of the servitude from which the men had fled had been used on 
trip in the past his back is a jungle of ugly scars 
glory becomes trips story as well as shaws as the 
runaway undergoes a radical selfrealization in the end the 54th 
becomes the only family hes ever known 
zwick the emmyaward winning director of special bulletin 
and thirtysomething stresses visual acting in glory 
action speaks louder than words and he focuses on facial 
expressions and body movements rather than histrionics gimmicks or 
slick words 
he also is spare with dialogue when the 54th marches past the 
white regiments who regarded the blacks as a joke and less than 
men to lead the assault against fort wagner only four words are 
spoken by the once hostile whites give em hell 54 
ultimately color no longer is the issue the men are fellow 
soldiers about to die and like gallipoli and hamburger 
hill the overriding issue becomes the utter futility of war 
the battle scene at fort wagner is beautifully choreographed 
the men running along the beach the us flag full and billowing 
it is poetic and yet powerful 
glory makes good use of battle scenes they are exciting 
frightening and realistic at james island the 54th gets its first 
taste of fighting after firing a few rounds and watching a 
confederate unit retreat more confederates appear through the mist 
like gray ghosts and the battle soon becomes handtohand combat 
dan lerner was second unit director and bob minor coordinated the 
stunts 
glory is bound to be a contender at oscar time it also has 
a haunting but overused score by james horner with choral work by 
the boys choir of harlem the music is lovely but unfortunately the 
filmmakers use the same refrain so often that just about every 
scene becomes a climax 
there are good performances by morgan freeman street smart 
driving miss daisy jihmi kennedy as a stuttering enlisted man 
and john finn as the fierce nononsense irish sergeantmajor who 
whips the 54th into shape braugher whose theater credits include 
much ado about nothing and king john at the new york 
shakespeare festival makes his film debut in glory and is 
someone to watch jane alexander appears as shaws mother 
the freddie fields production has a running time of 122 minutes 
and is rated r 
</TEXT>
