casolo and two salvadoran friends were arrested nov 26 in a 
police raid on her house she was charged with terrorism 
possessing weapons of war and criminal association all of which 
she denied there was no immediate word on the cases against those 
two salvadorans 
in the walled garden behind the house police said they dug up 
103 mortar shells 213 blocks of dynamite 405 detonators 150 feet 
of slowburning fuse and 21945 rounds of ammunition for 
sovietmade automatic rifles 
she said she did not know how the materiel got into the yard of 
her rented home on the northwestern edge of san salvador 
cristiani denied his rightist administration was pressured to 
free casolo by the united states the key financial supporter of 
his government 
the judges decision to release her is strictly judicial he 
said it is a political decision that we have made to deport 
her 
judge guillermo romero of the criminal court handled the case 
cristiani said he spoke with sen dodd who telephoned several 
times to ask about the case but at no time did sen dodd try to 
exert pressure indeed his position was that if there was 
sufficient proof against her her trial should go forward 
dodd said earlier wednesday he was told in telephone 
conversations with salvadoran officials including cristiani that 
casolo would be freed and expelled by thursday afternoon 
a statement issued by his office said cristiani informs me 
that the judge in her case has ultimately concluded the charges 
against jennifer were not fully supported by the evidence and that 
she could not thus be fairly prosecuted under salvadoran law 
casolo spent five years in el salvador working for christian 
education seminars which organizes tours for americans to learn 
