the ruling political partys plan to put 
up africas tallest building in a park set aside 26 years ago for 
the common man stirred enough outrage in environmentalist wangari 
maathai that she went to court to stop it 
that raised the hackles of parliament which held her action to 
be tantamount to suing the head of state and the court eventually 
threw the case out as lacking merit 
but not before the issue raised a public outcry rarely seen in 
kenya officials found themselves accused of being irresponsible 
insensitive and unaccountable 
soon after independence from britain in 1963 kenyas first 
president jomo kenyatta dedicated the 10acre park on the edge of 
nairobi for the use of everyday kenyans he called it uhuru 
swahili for freedom 
today the park is an oasis that offers an inexpensive respite 
for nairobis thousands of day laborers many of them lacking 
money for lunch use the park for what sarcastically is known as an 
airburger a lunchhour nap 
after plans for the park were announced by the kenya african 
national union the nations only legal political party president 
daniel arap moi allowed debate to go on for a little more than a 
month then he assailed the buildings critics as having insects 
in their head and told them to shut up 
his order silenced most of the buildings detracters 
not mrs maathai she went to court despite parliaments threats 
to have her green belt movement treeplanting organization banned 
the park has a processional a pond with recreational row boats 
walkways and tiered levels for relaxing and picknicking it 
provides a getaway for the wananchi common people living in 
the crowded neighborhoods and slums ringing the city 
scores of citizens in letters printed by kenyas two independent 
newspapers pleaded with the government to put the complex elsewhere 
they like mrs maathai have been dismissed as ignorant and 
subversive by the governments most vocal stalwarts in a country 
where views contrary to the official position are strongly 
discouraged 
in a letter to the standard mrs r mwangi wrote i use the 
park with my family most weekends i see people there who have no 
other forms of recreation with their families men with wives and 
barefoot children but happy to have those moments of tranquility 
when they can forget the struggle of daily living 
please have a care for the wananchi we are already suffering 
from other problems 
kenyas leaders maintain the project will lend prestige to what 
already is one of africas most developed and prosperous cities and 
will provide thousands of needed jobs 
critics dont dispute these aspects of the project they say 
they just want the building moved to one of the other vast open 
areas surrounding the city 
the complex which is expected to cost 197 million and take 
about four years to complete will include a 60story main tower 
with a fourstory statue of president moi in front two 10story 
wings an auditorium parking for 2000 people and conference 
facilities for 5000 people even though a conference center 
already exists just a quarter of a mile from the proposed site 
in a public statement the architectural association of kenya 
protested putting the project in the park it contended the 
building will destroy the grassy belt on nairobis perimeter that 
earned the metropolis the name green city in the sun 
mrs maathai has earned the most vehement and vitriolic 
condemnation from parliament for her outspoken criticism of the 
building which has continued despite the presidents directive for 
people like her to shut up 
mrs maathai initially was reviled for her protests in letters 
to individual members of parliament the british high commissioner 
ambassador and the british media magnate robert maxwell who owns 
a share of the ruling partys media interests she also called on 
the people of nairobi to stand up and raise their voices 
she drew even harsher rebukes for seeking a court injunction to 
bar construction of the complex members of parliament assailed her 
12yearold green belt movement as bogus and subversive 
on dec 11 the high court dismissed her suit a nonstarter 
from the date of filing 
mrs maathai who before the ruling accused the court of being 
more concerned with politics than law said she was 
disappointed in the decision but would appeal it to the attorney 
generals office 
the most important thing is to rise and express ones opinion 
and say no when you should say no she said if we are not 
listened to then at least we have done what we could do within our 
own constraints 
