<TEXT>
losing the fight to prevent an increase in the 
minimum wage has left the us chamber of commerce in a somewhat 
sullen mood about the immediate economic consequences 
it will the chamber says result in the loss of hundreds of 
thousands of job opportunities ignite a new round of wage 
inflation raise the deficit compromise us competitiveness and 
force some companies to forego expansion 
the chamber was in the forefront of opposition to the increase 
which takes the hourly minimum to 425 from 335 and it still 
smarts from the defeat saying it resulted when sound economics 
fell victim to political expediency 
more recently it expressed its ire in the business advocate a 
monthly newspaper delivered to members and opinion leaders saying 
the inrease will have a ripple effect on workers in higherpaying 
jobs 
when wages at one level increase employees at higher levels 
place a new and greater value on their services said bob martin 
director of the chambers employee relations policy center 
he said numerous studies concur in his finding that the increase 
will cost jobs he cited one by the congressional budget office 
that indicated between 125000 and 800000 jobs would be lost if 
the rate were raised to 455 as once proposed 
congress and the white house agreed however to a lesser 
increase bringing the minimum to 380 on april 1 1990 and to 
425 one year later it also permits a lower shortterm training 
wage for some teenagers 
martin cites a 1981 report by the minimum wage study commission 
named by former president carter that found that each 10 percent 
increase in the minimum wage has the potential to raise the 
nations payroll by 076 percent 
since the new law will raise the wage 27 percent the business 
advocate article concludes that labor costs will rise by about 205 
percent or more than 46 billion 
martin did express satisfaction that though we lost the last 
battle we saved businesses more than 9 billion by holding off a 
wage increase for the past three years and that it helped push 
through a training wage 
the latter opposed by organized labor will allow employers to 
pay a lower minimum wage for three months to firsttime workers 
under age 20 the training wage of 335 would begin april 1 1990 
rising to 361 a year later 
while the minimum wage puts a base under minimum wages in much 
of the nation it is already exceeded in other areas with some 
food outlets already paying 6 an hour or even more for unskilled 
workers 
the chamber article didnt address another criticism of the 
higher minimum one made by william dunkelberg dean of temple 
universitys business school that the increases might not be as 
effective as believed in reducing poverty levels 
dunkelberg testified during hearings held prior to the laws 
signing on nov 17 that many earning the minimum are not primary 
breadwinners in their families but instead are relatively 
comfortable people earning second incomes 
regardless of who gets the minimum wage and the automatic 
increases that lift it over the next two years the chamber said it 
expects those earning above the minimum are likely as a 
consequence of the law to want more 
expect wage pressure it warned 
