<TEXT>
the crater of pan am flight 103 the 
deepest most visible scar on the town where it fell is 
disappearing under new homes 
at the end of november contractors began building 11 houses in 
sherwood crescent where the falling wreckage of the boeing 747 
killed 11 residents of lockerbie last dec 21 the final deaths of 
a terrorist bombing that killed the 259 passengers and crew of 
flight 103 
some people needed an awful lot of sustaining just to get to 
this week said malcolm mcgeorge who directs a team of social 
workers in the town 
the frustration that it has taken so long to rebuild has been 
very great crushing for some people others have little interest 
because they dont really want to go back but feel they have to go 
back because so much effort has been put in by so many people 
the crater has been filled and the street restored burnt shells 
of houses have been pulled down and only muddy vacant lots betray 
the extent of the destruction 
the construction reflects the determination to wipe out all 
traces of the disaster along the sidewalk of sherwood crescent 
however a lone pot of flowers testifies to a town torn between 
remembrance and forgetting 
lockerbie lost its quiet obscurity just after 703 that cold 
wednesday night when explosives hidden in a radiocassette 
recorder shattered the pan am jet maid of the seas at 36 
seconds past 703 the eskdalemuir observatory 15 miles from 
lockerbie recorded seismic shocks apparently caused by the falling 
wreckage 
the main part of the fuselage with enough jet fuel to push a 
747 from scotland to new york exploded in sherwood crescent 
shattered metal and flaming fuel spewed over dozens of houses and 
debris blocked traffic on the fourlane northsouth highway 
a forward portion of the fuselage landed across town in rosebank 
crescent the planes nose fell 3 miles from town across the road 
from the stone church at tundergarth 
the night it happened one of the first things i saw was the 
body of a child hanging in a tree said ronnie hall who lives in 
the rosebank area that child will never leave me 
the towns population of 3500 nearly doubled with the influx of 
a thousand police officers 700 military personnel 500 other 
volunteer and support workers and hundreds of reporters 
photographers and camera crews 
sheep now graze placidly where the planes nose fell and the two 
shattered houses in rosebank crescent have been rebuilt but the 
memories remain 
when you think the number of houses in rosebank that face in 
that small area where 61 bodies were found there must be more 
than a hundred people who could not avoid seeing that mayhem 
mcgeorge said 
sandy pelling assistant director of social work for the 
dumfries and galloway regional council recalled one family that 
identified with the young boy that was lying in their garden for 
two days they started grieving for him they wanted to know his 
name 
robert hunter whose home was 120 yards from the sherwood 
crescent crater brought his family back to the house two days 
after the disaster we wanted back in to settle the kids if 
nothing else he said 
repairs put them out of the house for six weeks however and it 
was 10 months before the job was complete but they never thought 
of moving he said 
before talking with a reporter hunter shooed his daughters out 
of the parlor talk of the disaster upsets them he said and with 
the onset of winter he realized his older daughter now 5 had 
become afraid of the dark 
we do talk about it with them on their own they understand 
what happened he said 
in the months after the disaster some adults as well as 
children had difficulty sleeping mcgeorge said 
there were reports of children not sleeping or having 
nightmares or playing what their parents thought were rather 
bizarre unsavory games playing airplanes and crashing them and 
so on he said but thats definitely understandable and 
people were encouraged to understand that was ok that it was a way 
of dealing with it 
he said there have been no reports of children developing 
serious behavioral problems 
i think the people with the serious and lasting problems are 
in the uniformed services just because of what they had to do 
in the recovery of bodies mcgeorge said 
the torn bodies reawakened some mens memories of combat 
service in one case going back to world war i he said for some 
women the disaster brought back moments of great personal loss 
of a husband a child or parents 
one of the things you hear people say is that they dont feel 
safe anymore if it happened once it can happen again mcgeorge 
said some of them are quite unable to use public transport 
buses or trains airplanes are just out of the question 
mcgeorge said some residents have admitted fearing the dark or 
the noise of a passing truck or express train when one lockerbie 
man took a train to london his wife kept the television on all day 
expecting news of a rail disaster 
reflecting on the work in lockerbie pelling talks about the 
timelessness of disaster for survivors 
it is there it has happened it is always going to be 
there he said while they desperately want to get this episode 
behind them and feel they are going forward they are not going to 
be able to shake off the night of the 21st in quite as easy terms 
agencies that came to help are thinking now of leaving 
i think we should melt away were another scar of the 
disaster said alex mcelroy who directs the community support 
office set up by the regional council 
mcelroys office runs by two clocks one set on us eastern 
standard time because some of its contacts are with authorities and 
insurors in the united states as well as with relatives of the 
american victims 
the approach of the anniversary made memories unavoidable on 
the afternoon of dec 21 the town will dedicate a monument in the 
dryfesdale cemetery bearing the names of the 270 dead a memorial 
service will be held that night outside the town hall used a year 
ago as a temporary mortuary some american relatives of victims 
plan to attend 
were hoping that after the 21st we can get back and have our 
town to ourselves said valerie moloney who works with a 
childrens group formed after the disaster 
hugh young a member of the district council agreed i think 
they see it as a watershed a time for looking forward again i 
think people hope the anniversary will be an end to the media 
attention 
