<DOCNO> AP891213-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
drug enforcement officials are declaring a 
partial victory in one battle of the war on drugs the diversion of 
prescription drugs to the illicit market 
cases of prescription drug abuse reported to the national drug 
abuse warning network have fallen by almost onethird since 1981 
but some medical professionals say the tougher new rules are 
preventing effective treatment of many americans with legitimate 
needs for such medication 
in 1981 131618 incidents of pharmaceutical abuse were reported 
to the warning network but by 1988 that number had dropped to 
88525 said gene haislip of the drug enforcement administration 
this is the one part of the drug problem where we have made 
genuine progress and reduced the size of it said haislip deas 
diversion control chief 
and yet the diversion of legal drugs remains a very large 
problem he said 
most frequently abused are the narcotic painkillers percodan 
dilaudid and codeine the stimulants amphetamine and preludin both 
prescribed for shortterm treatment of obesity the sedative 
doriden and tranquilizers such as valium librium xanax and 
diazepam 
the profit potential in diverted drugs is huge a single 4 
milligram tablet of dilaudid costs a bonafide patient about 60 
cents but can sell on the street for as much as 60 haislip says 
he estimates that up to 15 percent of the 25 billion 
prescription pills and capsules manufactured legally each year wind 
up on the street 
the drugs reach the black market through several routes 
physicians who intentionally write unnecessary prescriptions 
patients who convince doctors that they need the drugs when they 
dont pharmacies that falsify records and thefts from drug stores 
the authorities biggest weapons in the battle against 
diversions have been tighter regulation of physicians and 
pharmacies and monitoring of prescriptions 
some observers contend the requirements have made life more 
painful for patients with a legitimate need for frequently diverted 
drugs 
physicians go out of their way to avoid attracting the 
attention of regulatory agencies write physicians c stratton 
hill jr and william s fields in a new book drug treatment of 
cancer pain in a drugoriented society 
as a result they underprescribe the dosage of opiates and 
fail to provide patients with prescriptions for drug quantities 
sufficient to cover a reasonable time interval thus making 
frequent requests for resupply necessary the doctors write 
this prescribing behavior is humiliating for patients 
take the case of a texas minister highlighted in a documentary 
film by hill who works at a houston cancer center 
the baptist minister suffering from cancer and seeking a 
stronger painkiller from his doctor was rebuffed as if he were an 
addict 
youre a dope head and im going to dry you out while youre 
in here the minister quoted his physician as saying 
in an interview hill related the case of another patient who 
was receiving a toxic dose of acetaminophen because his docotor was 
prescribing it in combination with codeine rather than a stronger 
medication simply to avoid the scrutiny that attends 
prescriptions for the most frequently diverted painkillers 
the deas haislip said the federal regulation specifies that the 
legitimate treatment of pain should not be impeded he rejected 
arguments that physicians are hesitant about prescribing necessary 
drugs noting that morphine prescriptions rose 300 percent from 
1982 to 1986 
thats an enormous increase but the statistics do not show 
any such comparable increase in diversion for that drug which 
leads me to believe that it is for cancer and most all of it is 
legitimate haislip said 
however he acknowledged that some patients may have trouble 
finding pharmacies willing to carry certain controlled drugs a 
recent nationwide survey found that only 38 percent of responding 
drug stores routinely stock an oral morphine preparation in many 
cases because of fear of robbery 
while some doctors shy away from prescribing the most potent 
drugs a few others have made an illegal living from it officials 
cite the case of dr john hall thomas he ran two weightreduction 
clinics in texas and was writing about 45 percent of the 
prescriptions for preludin for the state of texas when arrested 
in 1982 said wilbur morris of the dea in dallas 
prosecutor chris harrison said at the time that investigators 
sent undercover agent allen byrd who is not overweight to one 
clinic to buy the stimulant 
thomas told him they would have to make it look legal so byrd 
would have to bring four fat girls with him harrison said he 
came back with the girls all law enforcement officers and got the 
prescriptions 
thomas originally indicted on 63 counts pleaded guilty in a 
plea bargain to one count of illegally prescribing the drug he 
lost his medical license and was sentenced to five years in prison 
morris said 
the federal controlled substances act of 1970 tightened the 
rules for those handling drugs with a potential for abuse such 
drugs are broken down into five categories or schedules 
schedule i drugs such as heroin have the highest potential 
for abuse but no accepted medical use and can be used only for 
research 
schedule ii drugs are the most dangerous and subject to abuse 
this category includes percodan dilaudid morphine and some 
codeine formulations as well as amphetamines and preludin federal 
regulations require that everyone who prescribes or handles 
schedule ii drugs register with the dea that manufacturers 
distributors and pharmacies complete special dea forms on every 
transaction that patients have a written prescription that cannot 
be refilled and that the drugs be kept in a safe by the 
manufacturer importer and distributor but not the pharmacy the 
dea even sets production limits 
schedule iii iv and v drugs pose a lesser danger and are 
deemed less subject to abuse doriden is a schedule iii drug and 
most tranquilizers are schedule iv schedule v includes many 
overthecounter narcotic preparations federal regulations for the 
schedule iii iv and v drugs are increasingly lenient 
nine states have gone beyond federal rules imposing a 
multiplecopy prescription system with most of the states 
requiring the physician the pharmacy and state officials to retain 
a copy of each prescription 
officials of the states california hawaii idaho illinois 
indiana michigan new york rhode island and texas say such 
programs enable them to spot those who seem to be prescribing or 
dispensing inordinate amounts 
all the state programs affect schedule ii drugs some include a 
few schedule iii drugs and new york citing an alarming number of 
prescriptions recently added the schedule iv sleeping pills and 
tranquilizers such as valium and librium 
officials say texas multiplecopy program helped crack the case 
of dr thomas although the long lines outside his clinics in 
dallas and nacogdoches already had attracted law enforcement 
attention 
the white house conference for a drug free america recommended 
in june 1988 that all states establish such programs and the dea 
supports them 
the american pharmaceutical association the american medical 
association and some drug companies oppose the programs citing 
concerns about patient care among others 
edwin webb the pharmaceutical associations professional 
affairs director said schedule ii prescriptions go down 
dramatically as soon as such programs are instituted and that can 
hurt patients who truly do need large quantities of medication 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

