<TEXT>
dewey and matilda houck have seen the 
drug war from the other side fighting a sometimes futile battle to 
obtain painkillers for a 5yearold daughter being destroyed by 
cancer 
they raced to hospitals at all hours of the day and night to get 
prescriptions for morphine that were good only for 48 hours 
searched the area for pharmacies that would risk the possibility of 
a breakin to carry the drug and tried to comfort their terrified 
daughter when she asked the unanswerable question why does this 
have to happen to me 
it is tragic enough to lose a child but its awful to live 
with the terror of her agony matilda said in an interview at her 
home in this washington dc suburb 
kendra laurel houck was born oct 28 1983 she died march 3 
1989 a sixmonth failure by doctors to diagnose her neural 
blastoma meant that when it was discovered in august 1986 the only 
options left were experimental treatments the doctors told the 
houcks their only child would have had a good chance of recovery 
had the cancer been diagnosed earlier 
instead for the next 2 years the family suffered through 
experimental treatments enjoyed a 10month remission doled out 
dosages first of codeine and demerol and later morphine celebrated 
kendras fifth birthday and learned all about the nations drug 
laws 
two days after halloween 1988 kendras condition deteriorated 
dramatically 
from that day on it became morphine and even that wasnt 
real effective said dewey 
she would be screaming on morphine said matilda a gentle 
woman whose voice wavered as she tried to restrain tears it just 
wasnt cutting the pain she was conscious and in agony 
by the time kendra died her eyes pressed open day and night by 
a brain tumor she was taking more than 100 milligrams of morphine 
every four hours 
to dewey the real issue is access to morphine 
the houcks found that very few pharmacies carry the drug out of 
fear of robberies those that do generally have very little on hand 
for the same reason dewey said pharmacies refused to tell him over 
the phone whether they carried morphine because they feared a 
holdup 
the prescriptions were good only for 48 hours which meant that 
in times of need they would race to childrens hospital in 
washington to get one from the doctors who knew kendras condition 
but they could not get the morphine there because kendra was at 
home not in the hospital 
eventually they found a pharmacist who knew their situation and 
would have the morphine ready when they needed it he sold it to 
them at cost 
even then the price was 494 for a typical threeday supply 
matilda said 
i felt like the sick and dying are paying the price for our 
drug war she said 
these are not radical antiestablishment people they did not 
attempt illicit street buys of heroin for kendras pain something 
experts say would not have helped her or marijuana for her nausea 
that would have been an option to us had we chosen to do it in 
an outlaw way dewey said but it would have been 100 percent 
inconsistent with their lifestyle in addition he said they 
were concerned how kendras mix of drugs had it included heroin or 
marijuana would have affected her 
merely handling the morphine seemed odd to dewey 
it was strange to fool with this stuff that was verboten he 
said we had jugs full of it and we could not get enough for 
kendra 
after kendra died the nurse immediately cleared out all the 
leftover controlled substances destroying them in the presence of 
another healthcare professional 
i didnt understand why i couldnt just flush it down the 
toilet with the valium he said 
