takeover turmoil continued to cloud the future of 
united airlines as directors of parent ual corp gathered for 
todays regularly scheduled board meeting at the companys 
chicagoarea headquarters 
a new employee buyout plan that uals management drafted was 
received cooly by leaders of uniteds pilots and flight attendants 
and ripped by the powerful machinists union 
their response apparently has left chairman stephen wolf without 
a firm proposal for raising uals stock price and staving off 
disgruntled investors 
opposition from the machinists helped scuttle a 675 billion 
pilotmanagement bid for the nations secondlargest airline in 
october and their support is considered important to the success of 
a revised offer 
the machinists represent about 25000 of uals 70000 workers 
the plan floated by ual management in meetings with employee 
groups would value ual at 240 a share or 543 billion the 
chicago tribune reported tuesday quoting unidentified sources 
the plan envisions ual employees owning about twothirds of the 
stock and public stockholders about onethird the tribune said 
ual management would invest 30 million for a 2 percent stake in 
the company and be granted options for another 6 percent the 
report said 
if thats the deal its unacceptable we will oppose it 
said brian freeman an adviser to the machinists in a telephone 
interview from his roseland nj office 
freeman said ual representatives had not met with the machinists 
regarding a revised buyout plan he said the machinists objected to 
the price and other terms of the deal outlined in the tribune but 
he would not elaborate 
uals stock climbed 275 to 17675 in early new york stock 
exchange trading 
the machinists biggest complaint about the earlier 
300ashare ual buyout plan was that it would require an 
unacceptable level of borrowing the deal which had been approved 
by uals board failed when lenders backed away citing the 
machinists opposition 
the failed bid would have given ual workers 75 percent of the 
company with management owning 10 percent and british airways plc 
15 percent 
james conley a spokesman for the machinists in washington said 
the union also objected to any transaction involving uals two top 
officers wolf and executive vice president john pope 
representatives from ual and from the united chapters of the air 
line pilots association and the association of flight attendants 
