united airlines seeking to capitalize on the 
booming pacific markets announced plans to almost double its 
service next year on asian routes 
the demand for seats on united in both intraasian and 
usasian markets continues to be strong united chairman 
stephen wolf said in a statement tuesday 
the expansion will have the greatest impact on routes between 
major asian cities where united plans to boost capacity by 110 
percent capacity between us cities and various asian 
destinations other than japan will grow by 88 percent 
the airline said it will establish minihubs in seoul and taipei 
for connections to bangkok manila singapore shanghai and the 
united states 
it said the number of intraasian seats should more than double 
to nearly 48300 on a weekly basis by next august 
wolf said united plans to continue pursuing authority to 
introduce service between tokyo and chicago in order to link its 
largest us hub with its asian route network 
united is competing with other carriers in seeking government 
permission to fly the route 
