chrysler corp will rely on a strippeddown 
version of a compact car to fill a void left when the company stops 
making subcompacts a chrysler executive said 
the nations no 3 automaker will stop building its dodge omni 
and plymouth horizon subcompacts when it shuts down its jefferson 
avenue assembly plant in detroit early in february 
youll see that lowend replaced by a valueoriented pcar 
chrysler marketing vice president john damoose said tuesday 
the pcar is the dodge shadow and plymouth sundance built at the 
companys sterling heights assembly plant 
damoose said the subcompact replacement probably wouldnt go 
into production until after cars derived from the lh and lx 
platforms are introduced scheduled for the fall of 1992 
according to wards automotive reports a weekly industry 
newsletter subcompact cars made up 131 percent of the total us 
car market the omni and horizon the only subcompacts built by 
chrysler comprised 8 percent of the automakers car sales of about 
959128 through nov 30 
