<TEXT>
more than a dozen reports of problems with rudder 
trim controls on boeing 737s have been made since a plane skidded 
off a new york runway in september two federal agencies 
investigating the accident said 
the federal aviation administration and the national 
transportation safety board said tuesday they have asked boeing co 
to provide data on any reports it has received on rudders set in 
unexpected positions on its 737300 and 737400 model jets 
boeing spokesman dick schleh said the jet manufacturer is 
compiling the data 
schleh said it is not clear whether the federal request is 
connected with the new york incident this is just part of the 
information the ntsb accumulates in the normal course of an 
investigation like this he said 
ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz in washington dc said the 
agency has received at least a dozen reports including two 
involving foreign airlines of instances where the crew says it 
discovered the rudder was trimmed in a way that they didnt 
expect 
the board began receiving the reports after its investigators 
found that the rudder was improperly set on usair flight 5050 as it 
tried to take off from new yorks laguardia airport on sept 20 
two passengers were killed and 45 injured when the 737400 
veered during takeoff and skidded into the east river breaking 
into three pieces 
the board will decide later this week whether it will hold 
public hearings on the accident lopatkiewicz said 
faa spokesman david duff in seattle said his agency has launched 
its own investigation after receiving several reports of rudder 
trim problems 
the faa expects to receive further information from boeing next 
week and then will decide whether to order any action such as a 
design change or modification duff said 
the inquiries are limited to the 737300 and 737400 models 
because they have electrically driven trim activators earlier 
737100 and 737200 models have manual cranks 
the faa has looked into the incidents to try to determine if 
the cause was related to human factors or a mechanical problem or a 
combination of both duff said 
the investigations will include whether a crew member 
inadvertently activated the rudder trim switch and an examination 
of the cockpit gauge that indicates how the rudder is trimmed 
</TEXT>
