<TEXT>
computer disks purporting to give information 
about aids have damaged computers at british banks hospitals 
universities and commercial institutions police said wednesday 
the fraud squad at scotland yard police headquarters said an 
unspecified destructive mechanism had been found in the disks 
which had rendered computers unusable in 10 cases 
the squad said it had reports of the floppy disks being received 
by mail in different parts of the country from london to edinburgh 
in scotland there were no confirmed reports of the disk being 
received outside britain 
the squad said it was investigating criminal damage caused by 
the disks to computers at banks hospitals universities and 
commercial institutions the recipients were not identified 
two disks turned up wednesday in the mail at the london stock 
exchange and others were sent to the australia and new zealand 
bank the city of london police said 
the city police responsible for the financial district warned 
companies to be on their guard 
these disks must on no account be placed in computers they 
are obviously meant to interfere with systems city police 
headquarters said 
city police said the disks apparently contained information 
about the disease aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
an accompanying letter asked for a license fee of either 
189 or 378 depending on the type of license to be sent to an 
address in panama but the envelope was mailed in londons south 
kensington district city police said 
the letter warned in small print that if the money was not paid 
the sender would use program mechanisms to stop a computer 
functioning normally city police said 
computer companies said they believed addresses for receiving 
the disks had been obtained from pc business world a british 
weekly trade paper devoted to computing 
joe hirst an expert on computer sabotage told the associated 
press the rogue disk was not of the virus type which spoils 
computer systems by duplicating itself but a trojan which does 
direct damage 
the name comes from the ancient greek wooden horse concealing 
soldiers who came out at night to destroy the city of troy 
there are two programs on the disk said hirst former 
technical editor of virus bulletin and a consultant on computer 
software 
the first is an installation program and the second is a 
questionnaire on the risk of aids which will not run unless it is 
installed on a hard disk it then prints off an invoice for a 
company in panama but the damage has already been done by the 
installation he said 
hirst said he suspected the intention of the sender was entirely 
malicious 
money does not appear to be the motivation he said 
it may be difficult to understand but there are people out 
there who get a kick out of showing how clever they are they may 
have a grudge against the world they enjoy the idea of doing 
serious damage to people they dont know like those who put glass 
in baby food he said 
the alarm was first raised on tuesday by dr alan solomon 
chairman of a group of users of personal computers who said he 
received a similar disk the previous day 
if you have not installed it then dont it seems to be some 
kind of sabotage solomon said 
at the stock exchange an official speaking anonymously said 
you must be off your head if you get an unsolicited disk and put 
it in your machine 
the official said the disks would never have been put into the 
market trading system if someone wanted to find out what was on 
them he said they would have used an internal system for 
transmitting office memos 
